Inflation, in Europe, has slipped on the food
Accelerated inflation, as measured in the euro area, is mainly due to the rapid rise in food prices.
In November, the increase in prices in the 13 euro zone countries was larger than expected, after an inflation rate of 2.6 percent in October, an annual inflation of 3.1 percent was recorded, said the statistics office of the European Community located in Luxembourg.
Official forecasts indicated only 3 percent, Bloomberg reported.
Unlike the U.S., British and Canadian central banks, the European Central Bank (ECB) did not lower the policy interest rate by saying that the decline in interest rates, with the growth of commodity prices and the fall in the unemployment rate, would lead to the generation of an inflationary spiral.
The ECB would like to keep the inflation rate below but close to two percent.
According to one analyst, it is the Catch 22 for the ECB: "we must deter" inflation so as not to have to intervene on this subject later.
In Germany, the inflation rate of 3.3 per cent is a record in the last twelve years and in Spain it has risen from 3.6 to 4.1.
Inflation in the euro area took off due to the rapid rise in food and energy prices.
Grain futures market shares rose 88 percent and soybean prices also reached their highest value since 1973.
The price of edible oil and dairy products also increased significantly in 2007.
This year, the world price of oil rose by 52 percent, and last month a barrel of black gold cost nearly $100.
According to the ECB, in 2008 the inflation rate will rise from 2.1 per cent this year to 2.5 per cent, but in 2009 it will fall to 1.9 per cent.
According to analysts, the 12-month inflation rate remains around 3 percent, however, for the next 3-4 months, the annual average rate will be 2.1 percent.
At the same time, they expect the ECB to lower the key rate twice in 2008.
Gallup warns of government crisis
After a long stagnation, the number of supporters of Fidesz (Alliance of Young Democrats) increased significantly at the beginning of December, so since 2002, it currently has the largest number of supporters, while Gallup (Polling Institute) has never before seen such low socialist support, namely 13 percent.
For loyal voters, the difference would represent, due to the greater determination of the opposition voters, a support of more than two-thirds (71 percent) against the support of one-fifth (20 percent) for the MSZP (Hungarian Socialist Party).
According to the poll, the MDF (Forum of Hungarian Democrats) and the SZDSZ (Alliance of Free Democrats) are below the threshold of parliamentarians: their support is two percent in the entire population.
On the faithful voters certain to go vote, the number of supporters of both parties increased by 1 percent.
The economic climate has continued to deteriorate from the previous lowest point, the proportion of those who felt that the country's economic situation was particularly serious has never been so high, it amounts to 41 per cent and according to 46 per cent complementary the situation is quite serious.
After the more optimistic outlook of last spring and summer, families are once again more pessimistic about their financial situation.
For next year, the majority of the population anticipates an aggravation and only a tenth anticipates an improvement of the situation.
Last December, 71 percent of those polled, a majority never seen in Gallup’s previous polls, felt the prime minister was doing his job rather poorly than well.
13 percent of respondents have confidence or a lot of confidence in Ferenc Gyurcsány while 38 percent support Viktor Orbán.
54 percent do not trust the prime minister at all and 27 percent do not trust the president of Fidesz.
One of the indicators of the change in the political situation is the proportion of society who believe that dissatisfaction with the Prime Minister can be dealt with without a change of government.
While 35 per cent of those polled wanted the government and prime minister to remain in office after the October riots, that figure currently stands at only 20 per cent, and the relative majority (33 per cent) believe that holding new elections would be the solution to this situation.
When asked about the intention to vote, 60 percent of respondents said they would certainly vote and the additional 20 percent said they would probably vote.
For comparison, for a "legislative election to be held next Sunday", only 55 per cent of respondents would certainly participate and 15 per cent additional would probably participate. According to current intentions, the result of the referendum would not be in doubt.
74 percent of people would say no to higher education fees, 79 percent would say no to consultation fees, and 84 percent would say no to hospital stay fees.
When we look only at the same proportions among people who expressed their intention to vote in the referendum, respectively 81, 84 and 89 percent of voters would reject the introduction of registration fees, consultation fees and hospital stay fees.
Auchan is the most expensive, Tesco has increased its prices by almost twenty percent
The hypermarkets located in the Buda<0xC3><0xB6>rs commercial triangle maintained last year's average price increase of 16 percent with the difference that this year the VAT rate did not increase.
Article by Napi Gazdaság (Daily Economy)
This year, in the Buda<0xC3><0xB6>rs commercial triangle, the usual daily Christmas basket also increased by 16 percent on average, a value increase of well over one thousand forints was displayed in all hypermarkets.
Prices, “which had already soared” in major grocery stores last December, have no longer risen sharply compared to the previous high base.
Nevertheless, consumers are obviously shocked to see that items purchased well below nine thousand forints last year now cost more than ten thousand forints.
The Daily Basket in the surveyed hypermarkets exceeded by 91 forints, at least, the psychological threshold of ten thousand forints.
And the highest value of the basket amounted to 10,573 forints.
(In 2003, this value was 6,800 forints.)
The prices of unicum and live fish remained almost at last year's level, however the prices of turkey fillet, walnut and poppy have risen sharply.
In the stores, the price of flour and bread followed the data of the KSH (Central Institute of Statistics) but, at Auchan, bread from one kilo to 139 forints only was found.
The competition did not lower the price of the product below 200 forints.
It was surprising to see, also in this hypermarket, that the price of the two-litre Coca-Cola consigned bottle was below 200 forints, so it only cost 257 forints the consigned bottle included.
However, this year, in terms of daily basket, Auchan was the most expensive and Cora the cheapest.
According to our calculations, Cora increased the price of her Daily Basket by 15 percent while Tesco and Auchan increased them by about 18 and 18 percent respectively.
Comparing the most expensive basket of last year and the cheapest basket of this year, we find a difference of 12 percent while the difference between the cheapest basket of last year and the most expensive basket of this year is 21 percent.
Prices increased by 1,480 forints on average.
Last year, prices increased by 1,206 forints on average, while the impact of the VAT rate increase was already noticeable in last year's Christmas prices.
This process has perplexed the trade, hypermarkets could not visibly determine what margin to apply on products so they were unable to predict the impact of price change on consumption.
(If a trader miscalculates the rotation of a product, he may lose a large profit on the margin adapted to the intensity of the trade.)
Due to the change in the VAT rate, the price increase of the Daily Basket evolved so excessively that the most expensive basket was 1,720 forints higher than the value of 2006 whereas the difference between the cheapest baskets was only 844 forints.
This year, the difference was not so excessive since the value of the most expensive basket was higher by 1,630 forints than last year and the prices of the cheapest rose by 1,284 forints too.
Bringing the two seasons of Christmas closer together, we have seen a catastrophic increase in prices, in less than 20 months the prices of everyday consumer items have risen by more than 30 percent in hypermarkets.
(This does not necessarily confirm KSH's data: for some staple foods, the Institute of Statistics found a price increase of more than 30 percent in 12 months.
This is the case, for example, with flour and egg.)
According to the Daily Basket of the latter, this seems almost absurd since the price level of this product, already very expensive last year, has increased by just over 10 percent compared to the base.
According to the indexes, flour suppliers occupy a stronger position than egg suppliers because they have managed to get multinationals to accept the sharp increase in prices as well.
In the commercial golden triangle, hypermarkets do not complain, they constantly record good years.
In our experience, the majority of customers no longer look at prices in the three hypermarkets visited.
They buy everything in quantity, they take the food of long conservation by pallets.
On Wednesday morning, large queues formed at the checkouts of the three hypermarkets as the number of customers increased sharply.
However, according to our information, the turnover is less important in the province, many multinationals complain to survey companies that they do not even reach the expected turnover, not only for food but also for sustainable consumption items.
Many hospitals save money on disinfectants
This year, more than a thousand infections, mainly caused by the incorrect use of antibiotics, have been recorded in hospitals.
The hygienic conditions of hospitals, the insufficient number of beds, the overwork of medical staff do not help to block infections, says the chief doctor of the National Epidemiology Center.
Many hospitals are also saving on disinfectants
Not long ago an MRSA infection was diagnosed at the traumatology department of János Hospital.
Antibiotic-resistant bacteria have been detected in a man hospitalized after a serious accident.
The patient was isolated.
At the beginning of the year a similar infection occurred in the same place.
The injured from a serious car accident was released from the hospital but shortly after he had to return due to an MRSA infection and since then, doctors have not been able to perform a major operation because of the bacteria that is in his body.
As of December 10 this year, 1,094 hospital-acquired infections generated by a multidrug-resistant pathogen have been reported to the National Nosocomial Surveillance System, said Karolina B<0xC3><0xB6>r<0xC3><0xB6>cz, chief physician at the National Epidemiology Centre.
To know that it is the number of infections caused by a multidrug-resistant pathogen that has actually been registered in hospitals and for the rest we have no information.
About two-thirds of infections (683 infections) were caused by MRSA, i.e. methicillin-oxacillin resistant staphylococcus aureus.
One-third of people carry Staphylococcus aureus (SA) bacteria in their noses without it developing a disease.
Infections caused by AS (such as angina, tonsillitis, skin infections, traumatic infections) respond well to antibiotics, they are easily curable.
However, if antibiotics are used excessively or inappropriately, the bacterium, which reacts well to antibiotics, will develop a well-resistant bacteria that will proliferate rapidly in poor hospital conditions.
In case of temporary or prolonged malfunction of the immune system, this bacterium can cause serious hospital infections, such as traumatic infection or sepsis, on elderly patients, of small weights or with a weakened organism.
According to the medical director of the János hospital, there is nothing special about MRSA infections, these infections are part of the daily life of hospitals.
It is important not to confuse the infection with the epidemic, we do not find MRSA only where we do not look for them, said Tibor Nyulasi.
SAs are resistant to antibiotics.
“These patients are isolated, caregivers are wearing rubber gloves and protective masks and we have antibiotics adapted to treat them,” said Tibor Nyulasi.
A priori, hospitalized patients are examined if they are carriers of MRSA, however the infection can not always be avoided.
The sampling of the sample is not fashionable
The vast majority of infections caused by MRSA could be prevented, but the current conditions and circumstances in Hungarian hospitals are not favorable for preventing the development and proliferation of multidrug-resistant pathogens, says Karolina B<0xC3><0xB6>r<0xC3><0xB6>cz.
As this infection occurs mostly in hospitals and nursing homes, hospitals should monitor hospitalized patients and immediately isolate patients with MRSA.
However, microbiological sampling is not fashionable in Hungarian hospitals.
It should be noted that the National Social Security Fund does not fund these examinations.
Most cases arise only if the MRSA infection is detectable on the patient, said the chief doctor of the epidemiological center.
The European Union has stringent recommendations on the appropriate use of antibiotics in human medicine and there are Hungarian guidelines also for the healing of certain infections and syndromes.
Efforts must be made to target antibiotic therapy, i.e. microbiological tests should be performed to prevent drug resistance, but this is not always taken into account by hospitals.
Microbiological sampling is even rarer in outpatient and basic care, said Karolina B<0xC3><0xB6>r<0xC3><0xB6>cz.
Many hospitals save money on disinfectants
Scientific evidence shows that MRSA proliferates from one patient to another most often through medical personnel.
It is therefore essential to wash your hands, put on gloves and protective masks. However, significant gaps are also detected in hospitals in this area.
MRSA proliferates through infection transmitted by inhalation of droplets and through contact. However, due to conditions in Hungarian hospitals, the infected patient cannot always be isolated.
In addition, the rooms are often full, the beds are often too close to each other while in terms of epidemic, the sick should be away from each other by a minimum of 1.5 meters.
Unfortunately, we also see that hospitals, in difficult financial situations, are saving on disinfectants, they lack nurses, the sick are numerous, so the risk of contamination is even greater, said Karolina B<0xC3><0xB6>r<0xC3><0xB6>cz.
According to Karolina B<0xC3><0xB6>r<0xC3><0xB6>cz, in hospitals or preventive measures are respected, the number of infections is demonstrably lower or else the proliferation of the pathogen can be blocked.
Government project against MRSA
The treatment of MRSA infection represents an exorbitant expense for social security funds, which is why this infection is being fought everywhere.
In England, for example, the government has established a program to prevent or reduce the incidence of MRSA.
According to published data, this program is effective and MRSA infections show a decreasing trend in England.
The European Centre for Disease Prevention and Control (ECDC) has identified the prevention of the incidence of multidrug-resistant pathogens (such as MRSA) as one of its priorities, as well as the prevention of hospital-acquired infections caused by these pathogens.
The commissioner, who was involved in a fatal accident, was not intoxicated.
The official statement regarding the fatal accident caused by the commissioner of the 22nd arrondissement was drawn up.
It can be excluded that the commissioner of the 22nd arrondissement, resigned from his post since, who crushed a pedestrian causing his death last Tuesday, would have driven drunk or dizzy, said Friday Attila Morvai, spokesman for the Public Prosecutor's Office of the capital after the relative finding has been established.
The finding confirmed the first result of the investigation which has already found that the former commissioner had not consumed alcohol before getting behind the wheel
Last Tuesday, the former head of the police station of the 22nd arrondissement crushed a 55-year-old man who found himself in front of him when he turned, with his personal car, in the Kossuth Lajos street of the 22nd arrondissement. The man wanted to cross the road by not passing through the pedestrian crossing.
(Furthermore, the fact that he crossed the road outside the pedestrian crossing is not a mitigating circumstance, under the Highway Traffic Act a car that initiates a turn must allow pedestrians to pass.)
