Additional €400 million for infrastructure
János Veres, Hungary's finance minister, and Marta Gajecka, vice-president of the European Investment Bank (EIB), signed on Friday in Budapest three agreements worth a total of 400 million euros for a credit line to support education, transport and environment infrastructure as well as energy.
In 2006, the European Investment Bank (EIB) adopted a budget of EUR 300 million for the Hungarian budget financing of transport and environment projects to be carried out from the Cohesion Fund, of which a credit agreement worth EUR 100 million has already been signed by the parties, this time the signed contract concerns the use of the remaining EUR 200 million.
The agreement on the EUR 150 million credit also concerns the budgetary financing of education-related projects.
The EIB has approved a total of EUR 300 million for Hungary, the remaining EUR 150 million to be used later, following the extension of the credit agreement.
The parties have signed a contract of 50 million euros for innovation, the state budget will use this envelope first of all in the framework of the research and development project to be carried out at the University of Debrecen.
During the negotiations, the project of the metro line 4 was also discussed.
The parties agreed that they would discuss the possible modification of the initial contract when Hungary finalised the details of the financing of the metro with the EU.
According to János Veres, this could happen in the first quarter of 2008.
Since 1990, the EIB has provided a total of EUR 8.4 billion for the financing of 113 projects in Hungary.
The EIB grants its loans at the EURIBOR-related interest rate, with a grace period of 8 years and no commitment fee.
Bulgaria, paradise of the EU real estate market
The evolution of the Bulgarian real estate market is spectacular, the attention of all Europe is focused on this country of the Balkans little mentioned in the past.
What, or and who bought in this EU market that is still the cheapest but will quickly become expensive?
Analysis of the Bulgarian division of Re/Max.
Currently, in real estate, Bulgaria is unquestionably the most fashionable target in Eastern Europe with its cheap ski apartments and seaside houses.
In the mountains, the most popular regions are Bansko, Borovec, Pamprovo and Vitosa and, by the sea, Albena, the "Golden Sands", the "Sun Coast", the ancient Sozopol and Nessebar but more and more people are looking for a building in the region of Kavarna and Balcik too.
According to analysts of Re/Max Bulgaria, sooner or later, the central region of the country, namely Veliko Tarnovo, Gabrovo, Elena, Triavna, will also arouse the interest of investors and they are also increasingly buying in the very cheap corner of Ruse.
Sofia, the capital, also offers attractive opportunities, with retail and office spaces promising the highest amortization rate.
Bulgaria is on the best way to become one of the most attractive golf paradises in Europe and thus be a priority destination, after the summer season and the winter season, also in the other two seasons of the year.
More vigilant investors are already buying in large numbers, for example in the corner of Bansko.
According to analysts, people buying a building in Bulgaria are at the same time looking to change their life, their way of life.
Most of the buyers are English but others come from France, Belgium, Spain and more and more from Romania.
Maltese and Cypriot investors are also present. On the shores of the Black Sea and in the most famous ski resorts, we traditionally meet many Russian buyers.
Foreign buyers are divided into three groups, says Georgij Jankov, Regional Director of Re/Max Bulgaria.
People who plan to settle buy renovated buildings, at a price ranging from 50 to 100 thousand euros, or dilapidated old houses, at a price ranging from 5 to 15 thousand euros, which are then renovated.
The criteria are easy access and communication possibilities, proximity to a large city, shops and in general that of the local doctor.
The second group includes buyers of second homes (since last December, Bulgaria has been listed among the top 10 holiday destinations in Germany).
The third group is made up of commercial investors who buy in the hope of achieving added value in the medium or long term.
The price of real estate in the capital is constantly increasing due to an increasingly strong demand.
In the European Union, real estate prices are the lowest in Bulgaria. However, in the last 5 years they have increased by 21 percent each year.
The increase in real estate prices essentially exceeds the increase in wages.
Fodor and the Six Percent Hungarians
According to the communication of Gábor Fodor, Minister of Environment and Water, the meetings of the professionals will end on Tuesday, however, Wednesday, after the official opening, the negotiations of the ministers on the international climate regime after 2012 will continue.
Experts and politicians from 192 countries around the world will discuss the Bali Road Map, which is supposed to define the efforts to be made after the emission reduction period defined by the Kyoto Protocol until 2012.
At the moment, there are lively discussions on this subject between developing and developed countries.
The United States also reported that, for the time being, it did not want to discuss exact figures, while it was ready to sign an agreement on reducing greenhouse gas emissions by 25 to 40 percent from 1990 levels by 2020.
Another important topic of the conference is whether developed countries commit to providing financial and technological assistance to countries in need, excluding emission reductions.
An agreement was also signed on aid to developing countries.
The aid fund defined by the Kyoto Protocol will be managed by a board of directors composed of 16 members probably within the framework of the Global Environment Facility (GEF), said Piac és Profit (Market and Profit).
The Six Percent of Hungary
On behalf of Hungary, Gábor Fodor, Minister for Environment and Water, confirms the EU's ambition to maintain its role as a flagship in global efforts to protect the climate and encourage the signing of the new international agreement before 2009.
The minister explained that the EU is committed to reducing its greenhouse gas emissions by 20 percent by 2020 compared to 1990 levels, regardless of the success of the signing of the “Post-2012 Agreement”, and is ready to reduce them by up to 30 percent if other major regions of the world and/or developing countries are also ready to make commitments tailored to their responsibility and capabilities.
Gábor Fodor recalled that in 1997, the signatory countries of the Kyoto Protocol had in total targeted a reduction of 5.2 per cent and all 15 EU members at that time made the commitment on 8 per cent less.
Hungary has made a commitment to reduce greenhouse gas emissions by 6 percent compared to the level of the period between 1985 and 1987, our country will fulfill its commitment, recalls the press release of the Ministry of the Environment.
The stakes are high in Bali because the long-term international agreement on climate policy must be put in place in the interval of two years, otherwise the entry into force of the agreement would certainly be postponed after 2012. In this case, the commitments of reduction below the values provided for in the Kyoto Protocol will not be immediately followed by a new international system of emission reduction whose need has been stressed in the new report' s international climate change report.
The reduction of emissions would be delayed and the increase in the average temperature of the Earth of more than 2 degrees Celsius could no longer be avoided which, according to scientists, would have extremely serious and irrevocable consequences.
UK army recruits on YouTube
British Army units are sharing video-sharing footage of their operations in Iraq and Afghanistan with the aim of making themselves popular.
First, it was the British Air Force (RAF) that became passionate about YouTube: special units intervening in Afghanistan upload video footage of operations carried out against the Taliban since March 2006, the BBC reported.
These recordings, taken using miniature helmet-mounted cameras, are monitored at the air force operations headquarters in Kandahar and are then transferred to London where compatriots upload them to the Internet.
The political message is inescapable.
Air force soldiers have already spent 139 sequences on the net by this route and their "chain" was watched by more than 75 thousand people.
The British Ministry of Defence registered as "defenceheadquarters" in the spring of 2007 and it releases videos on operations in Iraq and Afghanistan while the Commonwealth Office and the International Peacekeeping Forces in Iraq (MNFI) also have their own YouTube channels.
Mission in Afghanistan
According to the initial objective of the air force, the videos were passed on the net to recruit; according to the Ministry of Defense, they were also used to make the general public aware of the real objectives of the army's presence abroad.
The propaganda published in this way costs practically nothing compared to the usual recruitment advertisements on television, Gordon Mackenzie, a defence consultant, told the BBC; on the other hand, it also inevitably carries a political message since it justifies in a special form the merits of military operations decided by the government.
The Americans made a game.
The army is annoyed because, apart from carefully composed and censored videos, amateur videos are passed on the sharing site that also present, for example, the death of soldiers: in the "official" propaganda films, a little hypocritical, the officers do not avoid talking about the losses but they never present the bloody side of the fight.
Moreover, many videos had already been posted on the net showing the areas of operations in Iraq and Afghanistan that were carried out on a real mission, but the British army has only recently been excited about the loading of these videos.
The Americans recruit a little differently by using the shooting game America's Army downloadable for free. In this game the player can put himself directly in the place of the soldiers as part of a more or less real simulation.
