The banks want to solve the crisis.
The Federal Reserve Bank of the United States, the European Central Bank and the central banks of the United Kingdom, Switzerland and Canada have decided to fight the financial market crisis together.
More than one hundred billion dollars will thus be placed on the money markets through auctions.
It will involve banks selling, through an auction system, the interest rates at which they are ready to borrow money.
For example, the U.S. Fed will auction off $40 billion and, in addition, it will provide $24 billion to the European and Swiss central banks.
This is the first time since the attacks of 11 September that the central banks of individual states have decided to take such concerted action to prevent or even reduce the effects of the financial crisis.
"This approach tends to solve the major problems of the economy, namely the growing lack of free capital that banks could lend," writes in his report to clients Bernard Baumohl of the consulting firm Economic Outlook Group.
“The concerted action of central banks has lowered the probability of a recession in the United States from 65 percent to about 50 percent,” Baumohl said.
Banks have already lost $60 billion to unrepayable loans, especially in the United States.
Analysts are still expecting more losses in the billions.
"If central banks have chosen this approach, it is because they have to really understand what can still follow," said ABN chief economist Amro Kieran Davies.
“I think the situation is really bad,” he added.
Central banks fear that if the banks themselves have difficult access to loans, they will lend more to their customers.
This would reduce consumption and plunge the U.S. economy into a recession that could affect economic growth around the world.
The central banks made this choice after the failure to lower the London interbank rate, called LIBOR, used to borrow on the interbank market.
This meant that banks still feared mutual borrowing, despite the fact that the US, Canadian and British central banks repeatedly lowered their interest rates in the fall.
"It will have the same effect as a further drop in interest rates," Greg Salvaggio of Tempus Consulting told Reuters.
