Cuba, the most beautiful island in the Caribbean
For visitors, it is truly an island of freedom.
Everything you expect from your holidays can come true if you make a good choice.
Golden and white beaches like snow, high waves or a calm sea like a pond.
Palm trees and all inclusive with waiters offering you on the beach a pizza, ice cream or intoxicating cocktails.
Kitesurfing, golf and roulette.
On the islands of the Caribbean Sea, you will not find this list only in its entirety, but enriched.
However, there is only one island on which you will find much more and that is Cuba, the largest and most beautiful island in the Greater Antilles.
At the time of the Spanish, Cuba had been the bastion of their invasion of America.
Christopher Columbus called it the most beautiful place the human eye has ever seen.
Havana became the depot and place of transshipment of the treasures that the Spaniards had stolen and that they were transporting to Europe.
Then came the American era.
The Hotel Nacional was built at the beginning of the 20's.
It was Lucky Luciano, one of the leaders of the American mafia, who had it built, since everything that was a crime in the US (especially under prohibition) was admitted and supported in Cuba: drugs, gambling, prostitution.
Among his clients were, among others,
Winston Churchill, Ava Gardner, Frank Sinatra.
In Havana, high-rise buildings grew and cars, belonging to the cult symbols of the 50's of the last century, circulated on the wide boulevards.
Ernest Hemingway bought a property in San Francisco de Paula, near Havana, and, in Coj<0xC3><0xAD>mar, he had his yacht.
The stars of show business and politicians from all over America left their signatures on the walls of the Bodeguita del Medio.
So, what about today?
You can leave your autograph on the walls of the Bodeguita of Havana.
In the bar of the Hotel Nacional, a luxury hotel, you will mix the cocktail of your choice.
And these cult cars still circulate in Havana, since jigoulis and fiats once imported have already long ago, in a climate so salty and humid, rotten.
Although Havana, especially the oldest part, is noticeably decrepit, nowhere else in the vicinity are there as many splendid colonial monuments as there are precisely there.
Other places become more beautiful, for example Trinidad.
Since tourism brings the money if necessary, its development has the green light.
In the last fifteen years, new hotels have grown not only in Havana, but especially in Varader, on the coast of Holgu<0xC3><0xAD>n province, and also on small islands such as Cayo Coco, Cayo Guillermo and others.
Cuba still offers a fantasy that is unique in the world and that will be appreciated especially by lovers of small trains.
The cane had come back from the plantations extended in the sugar mills on a narrow track by small steam and motor trains.
Their rolling stock has not been renewed for decades and this is how we can see small locomotives running, whose contemporaries are not elsewhere only in museums.
Where to direct your steps?
The majority of visitors do not miss the most famous places.
So there is no need to write long about Varadero or Havana.
Otherwise remember that in the property of Hemingway, already mentioned, there is a museum and that the one who loves this writer should not miss the visit.
The Vi<0xC5><0x88>ales Valley in the west of the island is one of the most picturesque corners of Cuba.
Exuberant vegetation grows there on a limestone soil.
Mogots, limestone balloons, and boulders swoop up from the valley floor, and, with fertile soil in their bowels, even its rotten rocks are covered with a very dense carpet of vegetation.
The valley is probably the place where the best quality Cuban tobacco is grown.
You will be able to meet the final form of this product if you visit one of Havana’s cigar factories.
Someone might also find it interesting that this is where the Chilean episode of Major Zeman was shot.
Trinidad
It was founded shortly after the Spanish colonized the island.
It was the slave trade and the sugar trade that brought him glory and wealth.
The wealth was embodied in the beauty and the city-window character of this small city.
Koloniáln<0xC3><0xAD> <0xC5><0xA1>pan<0xC4><0x9B>lská architektura, v<0xC3><0xBD>razn<0xC4><0x9B> ovlivn<0xC4><0x9B>ná pozd<0xC4><0x9B>j<0xC5><0xA1><0xC3><0xAD>mi francouzsk<0xC3><0xBD>mi osadn<0xC3><0xAD>ky, formerly <0xC4><0x8D>ty<0xC5><0x99>i stalet<0xC3><0xAD> tém<0xC4><0x9B><0xC5><0x99> nezm<0xC4><0x9B>nila.
Trinidad, located between the sea and the Escambray mountain range, is a place so remote that even in the 50's of the last century, there was no road that would connect this region with the rest of the country.
This isolation allowed him to remain on the sidelines.
We didn't build anything, and that's why we didn't demolish anything either, everybody just had a roof over their head.
If you have more time in Trinidad than an afternoon, then it is worth going to see also some interesting places in the surroundings, such as Playa Anc<0xC3><0xB3>n beach or the Valley of the Sweets.
Then, in the evening, it is customary to go to the Casa de la M<0xC3><0xBA>sica which comes alive after sunset and where the music only becomes dull in the early morning.
Baracoa
Some refer to this town located in the extreme East of Cuba as the most beautiful on the island.
This opinion is certainly already influenced by the path that leads to it.
The two roads leading there from Guantánamo must cross high, rugged mountains and traverse an almost unmarked landscape of human activity.
UNESCO has inscribed Cuba’s East Cove, thanks to its unspoiled landscape, on the World Heritage List.
The best chocolate is made there, in the church, there is the cross of Christopher Columbus (in reality, it was born about a hundred years after the journey of Columbus) and from the hill where the old castle stands and the current hotel El Castillo, we see several table mountains, the most famous of which is El Yunque.
About coffee, rum, cigars, the mountain massif Sierra Maestra, the Bay of sows and the island of Pinos, the Tropicana cabaret, the sanctuary of the patron saint of Cuba Caridad del Cobre, Santeria, African religions practiced by the descendants of former slaves, about all this one could fill a lot of pages.
But, as they say, it’s better to see it once.
In Afghanistan, Allies Are Passive, Says U.S.
According to the United States, the lack of soldiers and necessary equipment affects the progress of the mission in Afghanistan.
