Government Debt to Rise to $1 Trillion in 2009
The burden of a state debt exceeding 84,000 kroner falls on each Czech.
At the end of September, the total debt amounted to 842.7 billion kroner.
The government had planned to borrow 159.2 billion kroner this year.
As a result of better-than-expected changes in the state budget savings, the ministry reduced the planned amount to 152.8 billion kroner.
At the end of September, the debt of the Czech Republic rose to 842.7 billion kroner.
During the nine months of this year it has therefore increased by 40.2 billion kroner.
However, as of June, it has decreased by 13.4 billion kroner.
Today, the Ministry of Finance has confirmed its data on the state debt dating from early October.
The burden of a debt exceeding 84,000 kroner falls on each Czech.
Over the past year, the state has gone into debt of more than 111 billion kroner.
"For now, it seems that, thanks to a smaller deficit planned for next year, we could exceed the border of one trillion crowns only in 2009.
Next year, the debt should be between 900 billion and one trillion crowns," Patria Finance analyst David Marek told the iHNed.cz server.
The forecast of Next Finance analyst Vladim<0xC3><0xAD>r Pikor is similar: "We could exceed the trillion in the course of 2009.
The exact date will depend on the next budget that we do not know yet.
If it appeared that the political situation was changing, that policies were ready to save more, the date could be pushed back to 2010.
But I am not waiting for this change," he said.
Debts are growing
The state debt is constituted by central government debts and it is generated essentially by the accumulation of deficits in the state budget.
The government debt is financed by treasury bills, annuities, direct loans or, for example, by loans to the European Investment Bank.
The domestic debt of the state has increased this year for the moment from 38,5 billion to 719.4 billion crowns.
The foreign debt of the state has increased this year for the moment from 1.7 billion kroner to 123.3 billion kroner.
The so-called negotiable state debt reached 803.3 billion kroner at the end of September and as of June it has decreased by 13.7 billion kroner.
The average debt requirement of the State was 6.5 years.
“Total debt increased year-on-year from the first to the third half of the year by 13 percent, which is, given the current good health of the economy, a much too high figure.
It is interesting that the increase is generated mainly by the annuity securities where it reaches 20 percent.
It is bad that the debt is growing, but on the other hand it indicates that there will be something to negotiate when the pension reform comes," Pikora said.
Better than we expected
It follows from the government's debt financing and management strategy for 2007 that the government had planned to borrow 159.2 billion kroner this year.
However, at the beginning of September, thanks to a better-than-expected evolution of the savings of the state budget, the ministry reduced the planned amount to 152.8 billion crowns.
The sum is essentially constituted by the deficit of the budget of the State that will obviously reach 76 billion crowns this year, instead of the 91,3 billion crowns initially previewed.
Secondly, these are the maximum sources planned for the Czech Consolidation Agency, i.e. CZK 13.3 billion, the reserve of CZK 10 billion for the payment of pensions, the financing of government annuities for CZK 43 billion and the repayments of loans from the European Investment Bank amounting to CZK 1.8 billion.
She was appearing in court in Khartoum today for naming a teddy bear
The British teacher tried in Sudan for insulting Islam was sentenced Thursday night by a court in Khartoum to 15 days in prison and expulsion, said her lawyer.
The British woman was accused of allowing students aged 6 to 7 to give the name of Muhammad to a teddy bear while any representation of the prophet of Islam is illegal.
She was liable to a penalty of lashing.
The 54-year-old British teacher, who works at Unity High School in Khartoum, Sudan, was arrested on Sunday at her home and charged with Islam and sedition under Article 125 of the Sudanese Penal Code, following several complaints by parents of students to the Sudanese Ministry of Education.
The story actually dates back to September, when this teacher asked her students, aged 6/7, to choose a name for the class’s teddy bear.
“Eight names come out of the mouths of children, including Hassan, Abdullah and Mohammed,” said school principal Robert Boulos.
Finally, after a vote in the class, 20 out of 23 children chose Mohamed as their preferred first name.
Mohamed is of course the name of the Muslim prophet, but above all a very common name in Sudan.
The children then made a book for the class with the picture of the bear followed by the caption “My name is Mohamed”.
The bear itself was not labeled with this name, but the problem is simply that of the depiction of the prophet being considered an insult to Islam.
One of Gibbons’ Muslim colleagues, a teacher at the same school in Sudan, said he knew Gibbons well and that she would never have done anything that would be insulting to a religious faith, “I just regret that she asked the children to vote for a name,” he said, calling it an “innocent mistake.”
The opinion was shared by many of the teacher's students, who described her as "very caring towards her students" and "who never talks about religion in class".
Remember that the first name Mohamed is also the second most given name in Great Britain, it is written in English in 14 different ways.
This name often chosen by Muslim families is a way of honoring the prophet (often given to the first child of a family).
But what are the rules regarding the use of this first name?
For example, can you give it to a toy?
This is, of course, a question of interpretation.
