Tensions rise in Pakistan
Pakistani police on Monday cracked down on the first protests since the imposition of a state of emergency two days earlier by General Musharraf.
In the eastern city of Lahore, about 2,000 lawyers protesting against emergency measures were injured by tear gas canisters used by security forces, witnesses said.
The latter retaliated by throwing stones, injuring police officers.
At least 350 lawyers have been arrested.
Similar scenarios in Karachi and Rawalpindi, where police officers charged and injured lawyers.
Several would have been arrested.
In Islamabad, lawyers for the Supreme Court bar called for a general strike and announced protests, following a wave of some 500 arrests over the weekend of opponents, human rights activists and lawyers.
Streets leading to the Supreme Court were blocked off Monday morning to prevent the rally.
Other protests were reported to have taken place in Multan (centre) and Peshawar (northwest).
The lawyers’ movement on Monday garnered the support of religious parties grouped in the powerful Muttahida Majlis-e-Amal alliance whose president “urged the population to send flowers to the judges who ruled against the state of emergency and detritus to those who took the oath before Musharraf.”
"Musharraf's promise no longer holds."
The Pakistani Supreme Court is directly affected by the emergency measure proclaimed Saturday night.
It was to decide in the coming days on the legality of the presidential re-election, on October 6, by indirect suffrage, of President Musharraf.
The President of the Court, Iftikhar Mohammed Chaudhry, was ousted and replaced.
“Everything we are seeing is illegal, unconstitutional and contrary to the rulings of the Supreme Court,” he told The News.
Pervez Musharraf's promise to leave the army and become a civilian president "is no longer valid" after the state of emergency was imposed, Deputy Information Minister Tariq Azeem said on Monday.
He was expected to drop his military uniform by November 15, the date of the end of his first presidential term.
The Deputy Minister of Information also confirmed that the January elections could be postponed.
In addition, the Pakistani government has denied persistent rumours in the country that President Musharraf has been under house arrest by his deputy army chief.
