Spectacular repair on the space station
It took astronaut Scott Parazynski and his crewmates on the International Space Station (ISS) more than seven hours of work in space to make the spectacular repair of a torn solar panel, essential to the station's continued scientific activities.
A risky exit that has accumulated records because of its duration, its distance from the habitable modules, the speed with which it was imagined, the tools "diddled" by the astronauts to carry out the repair.
The problem appeared Tuesday when the astronauts had unloaded from the shuttle Discovery the module Harmony, a large cylindrical room in charge of hosting soon the European and Japanese scientific laboratories (see box).
This module is a kind of landing platform for laboratory modules.
We need to be able to supply them with electricity.
The crew’s second task was to move a 17.5-ton solar-panel power module already on the ISS to its final position.
After moving it, the crew began redeploying the module’s solar panels, which have a wingspan of 76 meters.
And this is where one of the panels, which unfold like accordions, was damaged over about a meter by a cable that got stuck.
The deployment was stopped so as not to damage the panel further.
The astronauts, who were originally supposed to perform a control exit of the Discovery shuttle, and then go to repair another solar panel whose rotation system was defective, were forced to devote themselves to the damaged panel.
And it was Scott Parazynski who was chosen to go to the end of the 30 meters of length of the remote control arm of the shuttle added to that of the station to carry out the repair.
It is one of NASA’s best spacewalkers.
Large, resistant, very dexterous, he has a very developed torso and long arms.
At the age of 46, this doctor of training was therefore charged with "operating" the "wounded" solar panel.
After thoroughly inspecting the damage, he severed the faulty cable and installed some sort of "slats" on the damaged area.
He was aided by a second spacewalker who remained near the airlock and, from the inside, by other astronauts including Peggy Whitson, the crew commander.
The tool he used, a mini-hockey stick wrapped in insulation to prevent electrocution on solar panels producing several hundred volts, was designed and “diyed” by astronauts aboard the station.
Once the operation was complete, Scott Parazynski waited for the panel to be fully deployed before taking inventory of his tools and returning to the inside of the station.
Yesterday afternoon, the astronauts were enjoying a half-day of relaxation before today, seven astronauts return to the shuttle Discovery for a return to Earth scheduled for Wednesday.
The EADS share sanctioned on the stock exchange
The EADS share is currently in sharp decline on the Paris stock exchange, after the aeronautics and defense group announced that it would have to spend between 1.2 and 1.4 billion euros to cope with the delays of the A400M.
EADS loses 4% to 21.96 euros currently on the Paris Stock Exchange.
The group was forced to revise its operating profit forecast for 2007 following delays caused by the slow development of the A400M engine, which conditions the aircraft's maiden flight.
The cost to make up the delay in the delivery of its military transport aircraft, announced in October, is "between 1.2 and 1.4 billion euros, including more than 1 billion for Airbus", announced the parent company of the European manufacturer EADS.
As a result of these expenses, EADS will be forced to announce new operating income targets (EBIT) for 2007 at the presentation of its quarterly results next Thursday, he adds without further details.
The group also indicates that the estimate of new charges is consistent with the six-month delay.
As a reminder, EADS' operating income fell by 86% in 2006, mainly due to charges related to delays in another program, that of the very large A380 aircraft.
Initially, the group planned a first delivery of the A400M to the French army in October 2009.
The choice of the status quo
There will be no suspense on Sunday at the exit of the polls: the Russians will massively opt for the party of President Putin, United Russia.
Confirming their aspiration for stability, even authoritarianism, after a very locked campaign.
Three days before the parliamentary elections, Russian President Vladimir Putin is today sending voters a televised message on public channels, already recorded but whose content is kept secret.
It does so as the head of the list of United Russia, the pro-Kremlin party whose victory promises to be overwhelming.
Yesterday, the president let nothing shine by welcoming foreign ambassadors, contenting himself with delivering a new charge against the West accused of meddling – his favorite theme during the campaign.
“We know the price of a true democracy and we want honest, transparent and open elections, elections without problems,” he added.
In the eyes of the opposition, this is far from being true.
She is denouncing a campaign tainted with pressure.
Communist leader Gennady Zyuganov said there had never been "such dirty elections, even in Yeltsin's time".
After the crackdown on protests last weekend, former world chess champion Garry Kasparov, sentenced to five days in prison for illegal protest, remains banned from visiting, according to his lawyer.
“The Russians have kept the mentality of homo sovietus”
Behind these unsuspended legislative elections, there are two questions that are much more open:
Who will succeed Putin as president?
The official newspaper published yesterday the date of the first round of the presidential election, March 2, 2008; the candidates have until December 23 to make themselves known.
Elected in 2000 and re-elected in 2004, Vladimir Putin cannot run for a third consecutive term.
No successor has emerged.
What role will Putin play after March?
Prime Minister?
Head of the parliamentary majority and the all-powerful United Russia party who would choose the government and the president?
In any case, in both the legislative and the presidential elections, the outgoing power will triumph.
It's a tradition.
“The Russians have kept the mentality of homo sovieticus, they don’t feel in control of their own destiny,” says sociologist Lev Gudkov, director of the independent Levada center.
The historian Nikolai Koposov, from the St. Petersburg State University, goes back further: civil society has fallen behind in this Christianized country five centuries after Europe; the famous communal spirit has delayed the formation of individualism.
After the liberal reforms of the 1990s, “Putin returned to the model of a paternalistic state, perfectly accepted by the population, especially since this new paternalism was not followed by terror, but by a certain economic ease,” says Maria Lipman of the Carnegie Foundation.
Today the Russians “willingly renounce personal responsibility” which they had briefly demonstrated after the break-up of the USSR.
“What’s the point of thinking?”
The phenomenon affects all social strata, including the business world.
And the administrative elite intends to preserve the status quo: 65 governors (out of 85 heads of Russian regions) head the local lists of united Russia.
The new freedoms imported from the West are often synonymous with chaos, as in the 1990s.
Opinion prefers stability.
In the name of which the Russians will not vote for the extremists either.
Conclusion of Tamara Cherednychenko, a 54-year-old professor: “What is the point of thinking?
Those in power are not too bad, why change them?”
A heavy memory
After more than 60 years of confidentiality, the Nazi archives of Bad Arolsen, which trace the destinies of 17.5 million victims of the Hitler regime, are freely accessible.
The 47 million archival documents, stored on 27 km of line in Bad Arolsen (Hesse), were so far available only for "humanitarian" purposes, that is, individually and nominally, at the request of a former victim or his beneficiaries.
The eleven states in charge of their management – including Germany, France, Israel and the United States – agreed in May 2006 to open them to researchers and historians.
The process of ratification of this agreement by all States being completed, the opening has been effective since yesterday.
Sensitive information
The access of historians to Bad Arolsen will make it possible to carry out research “in particular on the movements of prisoners, the population of the camps and the state of health of forced workers”, explains Reto Meistern, the director of these archives managed by the International Committee of the Red Cross (ICRC).
Until recently, several States, including Germany, opposed the opening to the public of these nominative documents, because of the sensitive nature of certain information.
Like the supposed homosexuality or mental disability of some victims of deportation.
The registers of concentration camps or arrest warrants drawn up by the Gestapo had been compiled after the war for a practical purpose: to find the civilians deported or subjected to compulsory labour and, possibly, to provide them with proof of their internment, in order to pave the way for their compensation.
Even today in Bad Arolsen, more than 300 permanent employees process tens of thousands of individual applications.
Yet for some of the scientific community, access to Bad Arolsen is of limited interest.
“There is nothing fundamentally new to expect from these documents,” said Prof. Wolfgang Benz, director of the Research Centre on Antisemitism at the Technische Universit<0xC3><0xA4>t Berlin in 2006.
The EU and India want to reach a free trade agreement in 2008
At present, bilateral Indo-European trade already amounts to almost EUR 60 billion per year.
The EU is India’s largest trading partner and accounts for 18% of its foreign trade.
The European Union and India hope to sign a free trade agreement in 2008, said EU Trade Commissioner Peter Mandelson and his Indian counterpart, Kamal Nath.
In April, EU foreign ministers gave the green light to the European Commission to start negotiations on free trade agreements (FTAs) with India, South Korea and the Association of Southeast Asian Nations (ASEAN), with bilateral Indo-European trade already reaching nearly €60 billion a year.
The EU is India’s largest trading partner and accounts for 18% of its foreign trade.
The EU is also its biggest foreign investor, but India is only the EU’s ninth largest trading partner, according to European Commission figures.
“A free trade agreement would greatly benefit both economies,” and “India would improve its access to a market of 450 million prosperous Europeans,” Mandelson said.
Europe represents the first or the second market for each of the first ten products exported by India, said the European Commissioner. The Asian and European giants exchange annually for "47 billion euros of goods" and for "ten billion euros of services", said this week the president of the European Union, Mr. Dani<0xC3><0xA8>le Duraso.
