Will there be a year-end rally on the stock market? Experts divided by the sub-prime crisis.
With less than five weeks to go before the end of the year, investors are already rubbing their hands in anticipation of the traditional end-of-year rally.
However, this year experts are not so sure that this will happen.
Banif believes that "from a statistical point of view, the month of December on the stock market generally has a positive behavior.
However, it is not appropriate to make forecasts exclusively based on statistics, since given the current context, uncertainties lie ahead in the markets, at least in the short term.
Although they are not in favor of the stock market gaining momentum in the last weeks of the year, these experts point out that "the stock market is nourished by the existence of liquidity, willing to invest given the lack of alternatives with guarantees, especially fixed income, affected by the effect of flight to quality values both in the long term and in the short term".
For this, they believe that the stock market will behave rather sideways, not free from volatility "especially because we do not know the impact of the likely decline in Fed rates, given the high level of crude and the danger of stimulating inflationary tensions"
Javier Barrio, BPI’s head of sales in Spain, agrees that this is not the right time to say there will be a rally.
“It’s not the best thing,” says the expert.
The Ibex, the Spanish stock index, has lost nearly 4% since November 8, when the index closed at 15,945.7 points.
However, not all experts have this negative view.
Juan Solana, an analyst at Intermoney, believes that the Ibex 35 could close the year at 16,000 points thanks to the reorganization of portfolios and traditional contributions to pension plans that occur every year during these dates.
However, the expert nuances that things will be a little different this year since he believes that the rally will take place from the second week of December, after the bridge of Constitution Day (December 6).
The analyst does not consider that volatility will affect the market trend.
For his part, Federico Olucha, an analyst at Inversis Banco, evaluates that we are close to technical levels and "that is why we could observe a rebound in the index that could be caused according to the information that arrives from the European Union regarding the consequences of the crisis on the credit market".
The analyst hopes that these will be positive.
Analysts agree to choose the values that will be responsible for driving the Ibex to new maximum odds.
Solana, of Intermoney, says that "this year the great values are back for him".
The expert would include in the portfolio the two major banks and some manufacturers "because when the date approaches, the electricity sector will be very expensive".
Meanwhile, Federico Olucha, of Inversis Banco, says the increases will be due to the bank and the industrial sector.
The constructors will also benefit from this rally, in case they start it.
“ACS has been recovering positions for several months and we hope that other manufacturers such as Ferrovial and FCC will follow the same path,” explains the expert.
Cyclical consumption will be the protagonist in the latter part of the year due to the increase in sales in the Christmas sales season.
On the other hand, the expert believes that technology companies will do it as well, although in this case there is not much representation in the Spanish market.
Five times for seven years
For the past seven years, December has been a bearish month on only two occasions.
The authentic year-end rally took place in 2003, an exercise during which the stock markets emerged from the crisis caused by the bursting of the technological bubble.
This year, during which the Ibex 35 recovered 28.17%, December recorded an increase of 6.68%.
It will be necessary to see if 2007 is the fifth consecutive year of gains (for the moment the Ibex has increased by 8.36% since January) and if it succeeds computer on its year-end rally.
Banque Populaire will open 200 offices open 12 hours from Monday to Saturday
Banque Populaire has decided to renovate a large part of its offices.
A total of 200 banks are located in the most commercial areas of Spain.
These branches, which will operate under the Populaire Max brand, represent a major change for the bank.
Also for the rest of the Spanish organizations, since it is the first group that decided to start betting on the uninterrupted opening of its agencies until 8:30 p.m., and to open on Saturday from 10 a.m. to 8:30 p.m.
Another group that has also reiterated several times that it would like to amplify the schedules of its branches, BBVA, even if it has not yet decided to take the first step.
It is about to strike a deal with unions to close 75% of its branches on Saturdays instead of opening an afternoon, but not to the public.
The results of the Banque Populaire experiment will be decisive for other organizations to adhere or not to this initiative which coincides with the business hours.
This is precisely what the Banque Populaire is looking for.
Attract autonomous customers who circulate in these areas to make their purchases in SMEs and shops on the streets chosen to open.
The bank wants to open these 200 branches located throughout Spain in about 18 months, since this is not the opening of new branches but a renovation of existing ones.
For this, the organization will modernize the branches it already has in commercial areas, adapting them to the profile of customers on the different streets.
