The climate of Venus could reveal the future of Earth.
Scientists said yesterday that Venus was certainly a pleasant planet to live on.
Data from the European spacecraft in orbit have shown that the planet is certainly twice as small as Earth, contrary to what was previously thought.
Venus is the closest planet to Earth.
These two worlds are about the same size, with similar orbits, although Venus is closer to the Sun.
Scientists now believe that billions of years ago, Venus may have had conditions similar to Earth’s, and may even have been habitable.
But the greenhouse effect due to carbon dioxide, atmospheric erosion due to solar radiation combined with a slower rotation led Venus to another kind of evolution.
Today the planet is devoid of water, is ravaged by hurricanes and lightning storms and has a surface temperature warm enough to melt lead.
The findings of the European Space Agency's Venus Express probe, which has been studying the planet for a year, offer a grim view of Earth's potential future due to catastrophic climate change.
Professor Fred Taylor, one of the leaders of the Venus Express mission, said: “We are beginning to understand why Venus’ climate is so different from Earth’s, although the planets themselves are virtually similar.
“Our new data allow us to establish a scenario according to which billions of years ago, Venus would have been originally identical to Earth, maybe even with a habitable surface.”
