Buses take people back to work, and to fight al Qaeda.
The first bus full of Iraqi refugees from Syria arrived in Baghdad yesterday, dumping these exiles without money or visa renewals, or others who hope the city has returned to normal.
Some have returned to fight against the militants who have driven them from their homes.
At Mansour bus station, even before Damascus arrived 800 people transported in convoys of dozens of official government buses, the terminal was filled with refugees from Syria and Jordan who returned by their own means.
“I decided to go to Syria after they killed several doctors in Baghdad,” said Sabah al-Qubaisi, a Sunni doctor.
“I came back today because I saw on TV and read in the newspapers what happened in Baghdad and saw that the city is safer now.”
“They say the Mahdi army is no longer committing crimes!” he said, referring to the Shia militia of clerical activist Moqtada al-Sadr, who has forced his men to move away for the time being.
Qassim al-Atwani, a 38-year-old Shia teacher from the Sunni-dominated Amariyah area, returned with his two children because he could no longer renew his Syrian visa and because the regime is preventing Iraqis from working.
Shia's neighbors in Amariyah called him to inform him that the U.S.-assisted militia, allowed Al Qaeda to be driven out of the western capital, and invited him to return.
One of Jordan’s newcomers is the leader of a Sunni and Shia tribe who had to leave his home north of Baghdad because of a grenade attack after he incited citizens to rebel against Al-Qaeda.
But he had to go home to fight.
“Two days ago, some of my friends called me and told me they had set up an anti-Al Qaeda militia in Sleikh, and they needed me and my boys.”
“That’s why I’m coming back today,” said Sabaah Alu Obeidi, 62.
Many say they have been drawn to the growing calm of the capital since U.S. troops arrived, and to the view of continuing training of well-armed “involved citizen groups” working with the U.S. military to defend their neighborhood.
But still others say they have been forced to return because of the visa problem and the decadence of the capital of Damascus, where more than 1.3 million Iraqis have fled in the past years.
Salaam al-Samarrai, 51, a father of three, expressed the suspicion felt by all about the exile visas that Nuri al-Maliki, the Shia prime minister, allegedly asked the Syrian government to limit to force people to return to the country.
More than two and a half million people are reported to have fled the country because of sectarian death squads.
"We had no problem until al-Maliki came to Syria and urged the government to stop giving Iraqis visas, to force them to return to Iraq," he said.
“I can’t trust a government that supports the criminals who burned down my house when I left.”
The drop in violence can be partly explained by the fact that Sunnis have been driven out of Shia areas and vice versa, creating places where tensions are lower.
There are fears that a sudden influx of refugees will once again increase sectarian tensions and bring the fighting back.
