Venus is the infernal twin of Earth.
Despite its hostile atmosphere to life, Venus is more Earth-like than previously thought: Europe's Venus Express space probe has discovered lightning bolts in the atmosphere and wind whirls at the poles, similar to those that appear in winter on Earth.
For nearly three decades, scientists have assumed that there are lightning strikes on Venus.
The European probe "Venus Express" has today provided proof of this - it has detected electromagnetic waves at the edge of the atmosphere: the flashes on Venus burst at a height of about 56 kilometers from cloud to cloud, reports Christopher Russel of the University of California in Los Angeles in the scientific magazine "Nature".
According to the famous theory of the cyprine, lightning would have caused the appearance of life on Earth: the storm would have stimulated reactions in the oceans that led to the formation of amino acids, the cornerstone of life.
“If there was life, it must have been at a very early date in history,” says Sean Solomon of the Carnegie Institution in Washington.
There should be hardly any living things on the surface of Venus today: the atmosphere is about a hundred times denser than on Earth, sometimes with temperatures of 500 degrees.
"Venus may be Earth's infernal twin, but she's still a twin," Russell said.
Why Venus, which looks so much like Earth in mass and dimensions, has been struck with such a different evolution, is the fundamental question of the ASE mission.
The departure of "Venus Express" in November 2005 was an important step in Venusian research, since no probes were on the way to explore this planet since the nineties.
In the opinion of the researchers, the most recent research results that have now been presented in several papers of "Nature" do not only emphasize the singularity of Venus within the solar system.
They also show that the points in common with the Earth of our neighboring planet are more numerous than initially assumed.
So the researchers found, in addition to the wind whirlpools already known at the north pole, a cloud whirlpool at the south pole, which rotates even faster.
The phenomenon recalls air currents in the terrestrial hemispheres in winter, writes a team of researchers around Giuseppe Piccioni of the Italian Istituto di Astrofisica Spaziale e Fisica Cosmica.
The second planet in the solar system has almost the same mass as Earth and is, with a diameter of 12,100 kilometers, almost as large.
The planet known as the evening or morning star revolves around the sun in just 225 days.
However, it rotates much more slowly on itself: a Venusian day lasts 243 Earth days.
Although Venus, with surface temperatures of 460 degrees Celsius and a pressure of 92 bar, hardly resembles Earth, scientists assume that the two planets formed under similar conditions.
On both, water accumulated and remained on Earth in the form of oceans, but got lost in space on Venus.
And while carbon dioxide has settled on Earth as carbonate, it makes up most of the atmosphere on Venus.
