These aren't Warhols' crates.
The one who connects the concepts Sweden and wooden case, thinks of Ikea, but not Andy Warhol.
Or is it?
At the moment, wooden crates made in Sweden cast shadows on the list of Warhol’s works.
A large part of the ninety Brillo-Boxes of "Type Stockholm" listed there are counterfeits.
After the Swedish newspaper "Expressen" questioned a few months ago the authenticity of the Brillo-Boxes of the year 1968 of Andy Warhol, the internal research of the Moderna Museet of Stockholm today lead to a disenchanting result: the six "Brillo-Boxes are so others", whose great director of the museum Pontus Hulten gave in 1995 to the Moderna Brine Muset.
The ancient history is entangled, a disconcerting sequence of artistic and curatorial productions.
In 1964, Warhol created in New York his first "Brillo-Boxes", painted wooden boxes, which are based on the red-blue-white design of the "Brillo" powder soap boxes.
An exhibition of his work at the Moderna Museet presented in 1968 - with Warhol's agreement - hundreds of Brillo boxes made of cardboard: These did not come (for financial reasons) from Warhol, but had been delivered directly from the Brillo cardboard factory.
These were not works of art, but rather their models, exhibition samples.
At the same time, Warhol had given permission in 1968 to have some Brillo wooden cases produced in Sweden, which were not exhibited at the Moderna Museet.
Witnesses of the time speak today of about fifteen wooden crates that at the time would have entered by right into the history of art and auctions, as original Brillo-Boxes of Andy Warhol authorized, with the appellation "Stockholm Type".
Some of them reached in auctions more than 100,000 dollars.
The problem now is that the legendary director of the Pontus Hultén museum claimed, wrongly, later that about a hundred wooden crates had been produced and exhibited in Sweden in 1968, which Warhol would later cede to him.
In truth, Hultén’s 105 cases were produced in Malm<0xC3><0xB6> in 1990 alone, for an exhibition in St. Petersburg.
By that time, Warhol had already been dead for three years.
Lars Bystr<0xC3><0xB6>m, Chief Curator of the Moderna Museet, next to the museum's six Brillo-Boxes, examined three others from Swedish private collections, two of which were made in Stockholm in 1968: their laminated panels were first printed and sanded, then applied with a brush of white oil paint.
The texture of the copies dating from 1990 reveals, on the contrary, that the paint was directly applied without a bottom layer on the laminated panels, using a paint roller - moreover it is not an oil paint, but an acrylic.
"These boxes have not been authorized by the artist and should be removed from the official list of Andy Warhol's Brillo-Boxes," suggests the director of the Moderna Museet, Lars Nittve: "If the 'Andy Warhol Art Authentication Board' exhibition in New York does not come up with another decision, the Moderna Museet collection will classify the six boxes as a copy."
As early as July, the Authentication Board announced, of course, that it would investigate the "heavy charges" that will be raised in the case of the boxes of soap powder.
But since then there has been an inexorable silence.
Rebel Soldiers in Manila Abandoned
In the Philippines, rebel soldiers are leaving, the same ones who had holed up in a hotel in Manila, and who had demanded the withdrawal of President Gloria Macapagal Arroyo.
Chief Antonio Trillanes, who accused the president of corruption and electoral fraud, told reporters at the hotel that he could not be held responsible for any bloodshed.
The soldiers loyal to the government had shortly before stormed the hotel with tear gas.
The two dozen soldiers had been holed up in the building for hours.
About half of them were standing before the courts on Wednesday because of a failed coup attempt in 2003 - among them Trillanes.
He took advantage of the audience to suddenly get away with about 30 sympathizers.
The military police, who were normally supposed to be watching them, had apparently deserted in his favour and joined his mutiny.
They broke into the Peninsula Hotel and demanded the removal of President Gloria Macapagal Arroyo.
The loyal troops in power cordoned off the area around the respectable hotel.
The President convened an urgent meeting of the Security Cabinet.
National Security Advisor Norberto Gonzales condemned the soldiers' actions.
"People have had enough," Trillanes said.
“We call on people to join us.”
Gen. Danilo Lim, who commanded the elite Scout Ranger unit, said other army units soon wanted to join the march.
Critics of the regime had called for a large demonstration against the president on Wednesday.
His government has been surrounded for months by accusations of corruption.
The financial district of Manila was already since 2003 the scene of the attempted mutiny of about 200 members of the army against Arroyo.
The insurgency broke down nearly 24 hours after the army refused to join.
Since 1986 there have been at least seven attempted coups against democratically elected governments in the Philippines.
